"""
MKT Context Commentary — Ezekiel chapters 44–46
Run: python3 scripts/zc-context-ezekiel-44-46-fill.py

Source data used:
- data/interlinear/ezekiel.json
- ANE background: Neo-Babylonian temple administration, priestly hierarchy reforms,
  standardized weights in ancient Israel, Zadokite lineage, jubilee land law

Key decisions in this range:
- 44:1-3 east gate sealed: contextualised against YHWH's entry in ch43
- 44:9-14 demoted Levites vs. 44:15 Zadokites: reflects historical high-place apostasy
- 45:11-12 standardized weights: connected to covenant justice tradition (Lev 19:35-36)
- 46:16-18 Jubilee land law: nasi cannot alienate tribal lands permanently
"""

import json, pathlib

ROOT = pathlib.Path(__file__).parent.parent

def load_comm(source, book):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    if p.exists():
        return json.loads(p.read_text())
    return {}

def save_comm(source, book, data):
    p = ROOT / 'data' / 'commentary' / source / f'{book}.json'
    p.parent.mkdir(parents=True, exist_ok=True)
    p.write_text(json.dumps(data, ensure_ascii=False, indent=None))
    print(f'  wrote {p.relative_to(ROOT)}')

def merge_comm(existing, new_data):
    """Merge new_data into existing without overwriting present entries."""
    for ch, verses in new_data.items():
        if ch not in existing:
            existing[ch] = {}
        for v, html in verses.items():
            if v not in existing[ch]:
                existing[ch][v] = html

EZEKIEL_CONTEXT = {
"44": {
    "1": '<p>Chapter 44 opens immediately after the vision of the Glory\'s return and the dedication of the altar (43:1-27). The outer east gate (<em>sha\'ar hamizrach hachutzah</em>) is sealed because YHWH entered through it (43:4). This is one of the most architecturally specific details in the temple vision: the gate through which the divine Glory returned is permanently closed to ordinary traffic. The closed eastern gate of the current Jerusalem Temple Mount is traditionally associated with this passage, though the Second Temple structure does not match Ezekiel\'s specifications.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>The sealed east gate</strong>: <em>Yihyeh sagur lo yipatach</em> (\'it shall remain shut and not be opened\'). The permanent closure marks the threshold as uniquely consecrated by the divine passage. In ANE temple practice, the direction a deity "faced" in their cult statue determined the gate used by their worshippers — here YHWH\'s directional entrance through the east gate confers a permanent sanctity. No human may enter it; no ordinary traffic may desecrate the threshold through which divine glory passed.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>The prince (nasi) and the gate</strong>: <em>Hanasi hanasi hu yeshev bo</em> (\'the prince — the prince himself — shall sit in it\'). The nasi has a unique, limited privilege: he may eat sacrificial food in the gate vestibule on feast days. This is not a general opening of the gate — he enters and exits through the same vestibule, not through the gate itself. The prince\'s special access distinguishes him from common worshippers while maintaining the gate\'s sealed status. The nasi category (not melek/king) is deliberate — see 45:7-9.</p>',
    "4": '<p>The prophet is brought in through the north gate to the front of the temple to see the Glory filling the house. <em>Vehinneh male kavod YHWH et-beit YHWH</em> (\'and behold, the glory of YHWH filled the house of YHWH\'): the return of the Glory (43:5) is now visible from a different vantage point — the front of the temple, not the gate. The prostration response (<em>va\'eppol el-panai</em>) marks this as the appropriate human posture before divine presence, the same response as 1:28 and 3:23.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>The divine instruction about the temple</strong>: YHWH addresses Ezekiel directly — <em>sim libecha</em> (\'set your heart upon\') — directing him to observe carefully: every ordinance of the house and its law (<em>kol-chukkat beit YHWH vekhol-toratav</em>). The double object — both <em>chukot</em> (statutes) and <em>torah</em> (law/teaching) — signals that the temple instructions to follow are both regulatory (how to do things) and revelatory (what things mean). Careful observation is a prerequisite for faithful transmission.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>Rebuke of the house of rebellion</strong>: The address shifts to the house of Israel as <em>beit hameri</em> (\'house of rebellion\') — a term from 2:5-8; 3:9, 26. The context of the rebuke: they had brought in foreigners to administer the temple. This oracle engages with historical practices of the Jerusalem temple in which non-Israelite personnel served administrative, custodial, and military functions (cf. the Canaanites in 2 Chr 8:7-9; the temple servants/<em>nethinim</em> whose names in Ezra 2:43-58 suggest mixed non-Israelite origin).</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>Foreigners in the sanctuary</strong>: <em>Benei-nekhar arley-lev va\'arley-basar</em> (\'foreigners uncircumcised in heart and flesh\'). The charge is dual: physical uncircumcision AND spiritual uncircumcision (heart). The Jerusalem temple had apparently employed foreign temple servants who lacked covenant commitment — bringing <em>chillul</em> (profanation) to the sanctuary itself. The bread, fat, and blood of the sacrifices require covenantal handlers; foreign administration profaned the sacred transactions. The Deuteronomic and priestly traditions both insist on the personnel qualifications of those who handle holy things.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>Failing to guard the holy charge</strong>: <em>Velo shemartem mishmereth qodoshai</em> (\'and you did not keep the charge of my holy things\'). The key failure: not guarding the <em>mishmereth</em> — the watch-duty that the priesthood was instituted to maintain (Num 3:7-8; 18:3-7). Instead they delegated this responsibility (<em>vatitenum lishmore mishmartechem</em>) to others. The temple was Israel\'s most important institutional responsibility; the sub-contracting of its care to non-covenantal personnel represents a structural failure of the entire priestly system.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>The exclusion principle</strong>: <em>Kol-ben-nekhar arley-lev va\'arley-basar lo yavo el-miqdashi</em> (\'no foreigner uncircumcised in heart and flesh shall enter my sanctuary\'). The restoration temple is to operate under a strict covenantal personnel requirement. This is not ethnic exclusion per se — the phrase "uncircumcised in heart" acknowledges the spiritual dimension that physical circumcision should represent. The <em>lo yavo</em> is absolute: this is a categorical exclusion based on covenant status, not merely ethnic identity.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>The Levites who went far from YHWH</strong>: <em>Ki im haLeviyim asher rachqu melay</em> (\'but the Levites who went far from me\'). A specific class within the Levites is identified: those who went astray when Israel went astray, ministering at the idols (<em>asher tavu acharey gilluleichem</em>). These are the Levites who served at the high places (<em>bamot</em>) throughout the monarchy period — officiating at the syncretistic shrines condemned by the Deuteronomic reform under Josiah (2 Kgs 23:4-9). When Josiah brought the high-place priests to Jerusalem, he did not permit them to serve at the altar (2 Kgs 23:9).</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>The demoted Levites as temple servants</strong>: The high-place Levites become temple servants — <em>mesharetim bamikdash</em> — with a downgraded role: doorkeepers, slaughterers, gatekeepers. They may serve the congregation by assisting with the public functions of worship but cannot approach the altar or enter the inner sanctuary. This is a demotion without expulsion: they remain within the temple system but at reduced capacity. The structure mirrors Numbers 18:1-4 where the Levites guard the tent of meeting but cannot touch the holy vessels of the altar.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>The theological basis for demotion</strong>: <em>Ya\'an asher yesheretu otam lifney gilluleichem</em> (\'because they ministered to them before their idols\'): the demotion is causally connected to specific historical acts of apostasy. <em>Vayiheyu le-beit Yisrael lemikshol avon</em> (\'and they became a stumbling block of iniquity to the house of Israel\'): the Levitical apostasy was not merely personal — it caused communal apostasy. Leaders who sin cause their followers to sin; therefore they bear amplified guilt. <em>Al ken nasati yadi alehem</em> (\'therefore I lifted my hand against them\') — the divine oath formula confirming the punishment is binding.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>Exclusion from the priesthood of YHWH</strong>: <em>Velo yigashu elay lechaheno li</em> (\'and they shall not come near to me to serve as priest for me\'): the permanent exclusion from sacerdotal function before YHWH. They cannot touch the most holy things or the most holy offerings (<em>divrey haqodashim haqodashim</em>). This is the priestly equivalent of banishment: they remain Levites but can no longer exercise priestly prerogatives. The prohibition against approaching the "holy of holies" materials (the sin offerings, guilt offerings) maintains the distinction between Levitical service and priestly sacrifice.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>The demoted Levites\' defined role</strong>: <em>Unetatiim shomrei mishmeret habayit</em> (\'and I will make them keepers of the charge of the house\') — all its service and all that is done in it. The specific role: maintenance and general service, not sacrifice. This defines their ongoing legitimate function: they are not cast out of the temple complex but reassigned to non-altar roles. The arrangement resembles the pre-Mosaic Levitical position — temple servants rather than priests. Their presence in the outer courts is acceptable; their presence at the altar is forbidden.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>The sons of Zadok</strong>: <em>Vehakohanim haLeviyim benei Tzadoq</em> — the Zadokite priests are elevated as the faithful remnant of the Levitical priesthood. The specific qualification: <em>asher shameru et-mishmereth miqdashi</em> (\'who kept the charge of my sanctuary\'). Zadok was anointed as high priest by Solomon (1 Kgs 2:35) after Abiathar\'s demotion. The Zadokite line maintained the Jerusalem temple priesthood through the monarchic period; Ezekiel\'s oracle validates this by making fidelity (not merely lineage) the criterion for advancement.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>Zadokite access to the holy place</strong>: <em>Hemah yiqrevu elay leshareyteni</em> (\'they shall come near to me to minister to me\'). The Zadokites\' privileged access has three dimensions: (1) approaching YHWH directly, (2) serving before the divine presence, (3) standing to offer the fat and blood. <em>Neum Adonai YHWH</em> seals the divine guarantee. The "fat and blood" recalls the priestly portions designated in Lev 3:16-17 (fat = YHWH\'s portion) and Lev 17:11 (blood = life). The Zadokites handle the most theologically charged elements of the sacrifice.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Linen garments in the inner court</strong>: <em>Uvevo\'am el-sha\'arei hechatzer hapniymit bigdey pishtim yilbashu</em> (\'when they enter the gates of the inner court, they shall be clothed in linen garments\'). The priestly linen requirement (Exod 28:42; Lev 6:10; 16:4) is continued and elaborated. Linen (<em>pishtim</em>, flax-based) is specified because wool generates heat and sweat. The theological principle follows: priests must not appear sweating before YHWH. In ANE royal court etiquette, appearing before a king in a sweat-stained condition was deeply disrespectful; the same logic governs priestly appearance before YHWH.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>Linen turbans and breeches</strong>: <em>Paarey pishtim yihyu al-rosham umikhnasayim pishtim yihyu al-motneihem</em> (\'linen turbans shall be on their heads and linen breeches shall be on their loins\'). The full linen ensemble: turban, breeches, and by implication the linen tunic and sash of Exod 28:4, 39-40. <em>Lo yacharzu baye\'ah</em> (\'they shall not gird themselves with anything that causes sweat\'): the explicit prohibition on sweat-causing garments. This is a hygiene-theology intersection: physical sweat represents exertion and mundane bodily function incompatible with holy service before YHWH.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>The two-garment system: changing at the gate</strong>: <em>Ubetzetam el-hechatzer hachutzah el-hechatzer hachutzah el-ha\'am yifshu et-bigdeihem asher hem mesharetim bam</em> (\'when they go out to the outer court, they shall take off the garments they are ministering in\'). The boundary between holy and common requires a physical costume change at the threshold. This prevents the "charging" of common space with holiness that would either harm ordinary people (if sacred holiness is dangerous) or pollute the holy garments with common space. The principle of holiness gradient — decreasing as one moves from the inner sanctuary outward — requires the priests to track their position in the gradient through their attire.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Priestly hair regulations</strong>: Neither shaving the head (<em>lo yegallechu rosham</em>) nor letting the hair grow long (<em>vefalua lo yeshallechu</em>) — they shall trim their hair regularly. The shaved head was associated with mourning (Lev 21:5; Amos 8:10; Isa 22:12) and certain forms of defilement processing (Num 6:18 — the Nazirite\'s terminal shaving after the vow). Long hair was associated with the Nazirite vow of consecration (Num 6:5). The priests occupy neither extreme: not in mourning, not under special vow, but in regular service — trimmed hair signals ordinary, ongoing sacred function.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>No wine before entering the inner court</strong>: <em>Veyayin lo yishteh kol-kohen bevoa\'am el-hechatzer hapniymit</em> (\'no priest shall drink wine when he enters the inner court\'). This extends the prohibition of Lev 10:8-11, which was given immediately after Nadab and Abihu\'s death from offering unauthorized fire — suggesting their disaster may have been alcohol-related. The rationale in Lev 10:10-11: the priests must distinguish between holy and common, clean and unclean, and teach Israel. Alcohol impairs judgment in exactly these areas. The inner-court restriction confines the prohibition to the highest-risk zone.</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>Marriage restrictions for priests</strong>: <em>Ve\'almanah vegerushah lo yiqechu lahem lenashim</em> (\'they shall not take a widow or a divorced woman as wives\'). Priestly marriage law from Lev 21:7, 13-14 is repeated with slight expansion. The Zadokite priests may marry Israelite virgins or the widow of a priest. The restriction preserves the priest\'s household as an extension of the holy — a wife of questionable or incomplete covenantal integrity could compromise the priestly household\'s ritual status. The permission to marry a priestly widow is a compassionate provision maintaining the priestly widow within the community of her prior status.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>Priestly teaching role</strong>: <em>Ve\'et-ami yoruvu bein qodesh lechol uvein tame letahor yodu otam</em> (\'and they shall teach my people the difference between the holy and the common, and cause them to know the distinction between the unclean and the clean\'). This teaching function is the theological rationale for the priestly system: the priests are the instructors in the categories of sacred reality. Without functioning priests teaching holiness-gradients and purity-distinctions, the people cannot navigate the sacred order correctly. This verse is cited in the NT as background for the teaching function of Christian leaders.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>Priestly judicial role</strong>: <em>Ve\'al riv hemah ya\'amdu lemishpat</em> (\'in disputes they shall stand to judge\'). The priests serve as judges according to the divine ordinances (<em>bemishpatai yishpetu\'uhu</em>) — the continuation of the role assigned in Deut 17:9-12, 21:5. Torah (<em>torati</em>) and statutes (<em>chukotai</em>) in all the appointed feasts. The Sabbath law: <em>veShabetotai yiqaddeshu</em> (\'and my Sabbaths they shall hallow\'). The priest as Sabbath-keeper and -guardian connects priestly function to the creational rhythms of Genesis 1-2 and the Sinai covenant of Exod 31:12-17.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>Priestly mourning restrictions</strong>: <em>Ve\'el met adam lo yavo letam\'ah</em> (\'and he shall not go to a dead person to be defiled\'). Corpse impurity (Num 19:11-16) is the most severe category of ritual defilement. The priests may only incur corpse-defilement for first-degree relatives: father, mother, son, daughter, brother, unmarried sister. This follows Lev 21:1-4 exactly. The restriction recognizes the priest\'s tension between family obligation (which requires mourning participation) and sacred duty (which requires purity for temple service). The halakha resolves it by permitting defilement only for those closest in blood.</p>',
    "26": '<p><strong>Purification after defilement</strong>: <em>Ve\'acharei tuharato shiv\'at yamim yisperuhu</em> (\'and after his purification, they shall count seven days for him\'). The purification process for a priest who incurred corpse-defilement involves the Num 19 water-of-lustration process, followed by a seven-day waiting period before returning to service. This mirrors the seven-day consecration of the altar (43:26) — the same sacred number governs both initiation and re-initiation into sacred function. The priest returns to sacred service as if re-consecrated after the defilement period.</p>',
    "27": '<p><strong>Re-entry to the inner court: sin offering</strong>: <em>Uvayom bo\'o el-haqodesh el-hechatzer hapniymit yaqriv chatato</em> (\'and on the day when he enters the sanctuary, into the inner court, he shall offer his sin offering\'). The sin offering upon re-entry after corpse-defilement is an additional requirement beyond Num 19\'s lustration. The inner court\'s higher holiness requires an additional purificatory sacrifice before re-engagement. <em>Neum Adonai YHWH</em>: the divine oracle-seal on the priestly protocol confirms these are not human inventions but divine specifications.</p>',
    "28": '<p><strong>The priests\' inheritance</strong>: <em>Vehaytah lahem lenachalah ani nachalatam</em> (\'and it shall be their inheritance — I am their inheritance\'). This verse is one of the most theologically concentrated in the priestly legislation: the Levitical/Zadokite priests receive no territorial inheritance (<em>nachalah</em>) because YHWH himself is their inheritance. The principle from Num 18:20 (\'I am your portion and your inheritance among the sons of Israel\') is repeated here for the new order. The material support (first-fruits, sin offerings, guilt offerings, devoted things) flows from YHWH\'s own provision to them through the people\'s worship.</p>',
    "29": '<p><strong>The priestly food portions</strong>: <em>Hamminchah vehechatat vehe\'asham hemah yo\'khelu</em> (\'the grain offering, the sin offering, and the guilt offering — they shall eat them\'). The three categories of holy-of-holies offerings that the priests eat in the sacred precinct correspond to Lev 6:17-18, 6:25-29, 7:6-7. <em>Vekhol-cherem beYisrael lahem yihyeh</em> (\'and every devoted thing in Israel shall be theirs\'): the <em>cherem</em> property — things irrevocably dedicated to YHWH — forms part of the priestly economic base (Num 18:14; Lev 27:21, 28).</p>',
    "30": '<p><strong>First-fruits and first-born</strong>: <em>Vere\'shit kol-bikkurei kol vekol terumot mikol</em> (\'the first of all first-fruits of everything and every contribution from everything\'). The complete system of first-fruits (Exod 23:19; Num 18:12-13; Deut 18:4) and contributions (<em>terumot</em>) flows to the priesthood. The theological logic: the priest stands at the interface between YHWH and Israel; first-fruits acknowledge YHWH\'s ownership of the land\'s produce, and the priests who represent YHWH receive this acknowledgment. <em>Lema\'an havuah berakhah el-beitecha</em> (\'so that a blessing may rest on your house\'): the first-fruits offering activates blessing on the household — the material exchange participates in covenantal blessing-logic.</p>',
    "31": '<p><strong>The priestly food prohibition</strong>: <em>Kol-nevelah uterefah min-ha\'of umin-habeheimah lo yo\'khelu hakohanim</em> (\'the priests shall not eat any bird or beast that died of itself or was torn\'). The final priestly food restriction: nebelah (died naturally/improperly) and terefah (torn by predators) are excluded regardless of species. This applies to birds and animals (Lev 22:8 for priests; Lev 11:39-40 and Deut 14:21 for all Israelites — though ordinary people may give nebelah to foreigners). The priests as holy persons must eat food that was properly slaughtered and handled — their table is an extension of the altar\'s purity standards.</p>'
},
"45": {
    "1": '<p><strong>The terumah (sacred portion) for the temple</strong>: <em>Uvechalleqchem et-ha\'aretz benachalah tarimu terumah lADONAI</em> (\'when you apportion the land as an inheritance, you shall offer a contribution to YHWH\'). The new allocation begins with the sacred district at the land\'s center — the arrangement is theocentric: YHWH\'s domain at the center, then the priestly portion, then the Levitical portion, then the city, with the nasi\'s territory flanking both sides (45:7). The <em>terumah</em> concept (lifted portion, elevated offering) from Exod 25:2-3 becomes here a geographic category — a lifted-out zone of sacred territory.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>The holy precinct dimensions</strong>: 500 by 500 square with 50 cubits of open space around it. The temple precinct (25,000 by 25,000 cubits holy area) contains within it a 500-cubit-square core for the sanctuary itself. The open space (<em>miqreh</em>) around the sanctuary functions as a buffer — keeping the most sacred structure physically separated from the surrounding territory. This spatial separation echoes the concentric holiness zones of the tabernacle: court, holy place, holy of holies — here translated into a geographic/urban planning principle.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>The holy portion for the sanctuary</strong>: From the 25,000 cubit measure (east-west) the portion belonging to the sanctuary (<em>qodesh qodashim</em>) — the innermost district. The dimensions create nested zones of decreasing holiness radiating outward from the sanctuary: the innermost square → the priestly housing area → the Levitical territory → the city → the agricultural/nasi\'s land. This zoning plan makes visible what the temple\'s inner architecture already expressed: sacred reality diminishes in intensity as you move away from its source.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>The priestly portion</strong>: The 25,000 by 10,000 cubit strip within the holy portion belongs to the priests who minister in the sanctuary. They will use it for houses and as a sacred place for the sanctuary (<em>liqodesh lamiqdash</em>). The priests\' residential allocation is tied to the sanctuary — their housing exists within the sacred zone, reflecting the principle that priestly life is an extension of temple service. This contrasts with the monarchic period when priestly families could reside anywhere; the new order grounds them geographically at the sanctuary.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>The Levitical portion</strong>: An equal 25,000 by 10,000 cubit strip for the Levites who serve in the house (<em>mesharetey habayit</em>). Twenty chambers (<em>lishkot</em>) as their possession. The Levites receive the same geographic extent as the priests but on the outer ring — their spatial position reflects their functional position: supporting the priestly service from a step removed. The twenty chambers (<em>esrim lishkot</em>) presumably house the Levitical families in communal clusters appropriate to their work-bands.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>The city portion</strong>: 5,000 cubits wide and 25,000 cubits long, beside the holy terumah — this belongs to the whole house of Israel. The city territory is the broadest category: unlike the priestly and Levitical strips which belong to specific groups, the city\'s supporting hinterland belongs to "the whole house of Israel" (<em>lechol beit Yisrael</em>). This democratic allocation ensures that the city (which includes the temple) is the possession of the entire covenant community, not of a privileged class. The city\'s inclusivity counters the priestly-only exclusivity of the inner zones.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>The nasi\'s (prince\'s) land</strong>: <em>Velanasi mizzo uvemizo</em> (\'and to the prince, on either side\'): the nasi\'s land flanks the sacred terumah and the city territory on both east and west sides, stretching to the eastern and western sea coasts. This allocation ensures the nasi is never landlocked or land-poor — he has territory on both sides of the central sacred district. The flanking position means the prince surrounds the sacred center without encroaching on it, representing his role as protector and patron of the sacred space without being its master.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>The land as the prince\'s to prevent oppression</strong>: <em>La\'aretz yihyeh lo lesegulah be\'Yisrael</em> (\'it shall be his land as a possession in Israel\'). The explicit purpose: the princes shall no longer oppress my people, and the land shall be given to the house of Israel by their tribes. The Ezekiel vision emerged from the context of monarchic land-grabbing (1 Kgs 21 — Naboth\'s vineyard being the paradigmatic case; Mic 2:1-2; Isa 5:8). The nasi\'s guaranteed territorial portion eliminates the economic pressure that drove monarchic land seizures: he already has enough.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>Direct address to the princes: "Enough!"</strong>: <em>Koh amar Adonai YHWH rav lakhem nesiey Yisrael</em> (\'thus says the Lord YHWH: enough, princes of Israel!\'). The divine rebuke names two specific crimes: <em>chamas umeshod</em> (\'violence and oppression/plunder\'). <em>Hasevu umishpat utzedeqah asu</em> (\'remove your violence and oppression and execute justice and righteousness\'). The prophetic tradition\'s central social-justice demand is repeated here: justice and righteousness (<em>mishpat utzedeqah</em>) are the standing requirements for leadership. Isaiah 1:17; Amos 5:24; Jer 22:3 — the same pair appears throughout the prophetic corpus as the non-negotiable standard for covenant leaders.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>Standardized weights and measures</strong>: <em>Mozney tzedeq ve\'eifat tzedeq uvat tzedeq yihyeh lakhem</em> (\'just balances, just ephah, and just bath shall you have\'). The demand for standardized weights and measures is a covenant-justice requirement rooted in Lev 19:35-36, Deut 25:13-15, and Prov 11:1, 16:11, 20:10, 20:23. <em>Moznei tzedeq</em> (just balances): the balance-scale was the primary commercial measurement tool in the ancient Near East; inaccurate scales were a systematic mechanism for economic exploitation, benefiting sellers who used underweight scales and buyers who used overweight scales depending on context.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Ephah and bath: unified capacity measures</strong>: <em>Ha\'eifah vehabet tochen echad yihyeh</em> (\'the ephah and the bath shall be the same capacity\'). The ephah was the dry measure for grain; the bath was the liquid measure for oil and wine. Equating them establishes a unified system: both = 1/10 of a homer/kor. The archaeological record shows considerable variation in actual vessel capacities labeled "bath" — finds from excavations at Tell Beit Mirsim and Lachish show bath-jar fragments with wide size variation, confirming that the standardization called for here addressed a real commercial problem. A homer/kor of ten ephahs/baths creates a clean decimal system.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Shekel and maneh standards</strong>: Twenty gerahs = one shekel; sixty shekels = one maneh. The shekel standard (20 gerahs) matches Exod 30:13; Lev 27:25; Num 3:47. The maneh at 60 shekels differs from some other ancient Near Eastern maneh standards (the Babylonian maneh = 60 shekels, consistent with Ezekiel\'s Babylonian context). The fact that Ezekiel specifies 60 shekels per maneh may reflect a correction of Judahite practice that had drifted from the Babylonian standard, or an alignment with the exilic community\'s commercial context in Babylon.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>The contribution rates</strong>: <em>Zot ha-terumah asher tarimu</em> (\'this is the contribution you shall offer\'). 1/6 of an ephah from each homer of wheat; 1/6 of an ephah from each homer of barley. The contribution rates are modest fractions — not onerous — establishing a regular transfer from agricultural production to the sanctuary economy. The specific rate (1/60 for wheat: 0.1 ephah = 1/60 of a homer if homer=6 ephahs, or 1/6 if homer=1 ephah) places this within the tithe tradition while specifying which portion goes directly to the sacred terumah as opposed to other tithes.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Oil contribution</strong>: The oil contribution: 1/10 of a bath from each kor (since 10 baths = 1 kor/homer). The bath of oil gives 1/10 of a kor, making the proportion consistent. Oil (<em>shemen</em>) was one of the principal agricultural products of Canaan/Israel alongside grain and wine (Deut 7:13; 11:14; Hos 2:8-9). Its inclusion in the contribution system reflects both its economic significance and its liturgical centrality — the lamp-oil, anointing oil, and cereal-offering oil were all critical to temple functioning.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>Sheep contribution for offerings</strong>: One sheep from every two hundred from the watered pastures of Israel (<em>mimashqeh Yisrael</em>). This flock-contribution supports the grain offerings, burnt offerings, and peace offerings that effect atonement. <em>Lechapper aleichem</em> (\'to make atonement for you\'): the explicit purpose of the contribution system is atonement-maintenance. The entire economic structure of contributions, weights, and measures is designed not for institutional self-enrichment but for the continuous maintenance of the atonement mechanisms that sustain Israel\'s covenantal relationship with YHWH.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>All the people\'s contribution</strong>: <em>Kol-ha\'am ha\'aretz yihyu el-haterumah hazot</em> (\'all the people of the land shall be for this contribution\'). The contribution system is not optional or merely aspirational — all the people of the land participate. The nasi is the manager of this collective contribution system, not merely a contributor himself. He receives (collects from the people) and provides (gives to the sanctuary) — the financial intermediary between the people and the temple economy. This establishes the nasi\'s role as the sanctuary\'s fiscal patron without making him its owner.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>The nasi\'s liturgical provision</strong>: <em>Ve\'al-hanasi yihyeh haolot vehaminchah vehanasekh bamoadim uvechodashim uveshabbatot</em> (\'and upon the prince shall be the burnt offerings, grain offerings, and drink offerings, at feasts, new moons, and Sabbaths\'). The nasi bears responsibility for the public worship cycle. This is the liturgical corollary of his territorial provision: just as his land allocation ensures he cannot be economically coercive (v.8), his fiscal responsibility for the public cult ensures the cult is adequately funded. The three-tier calendar (feasts, new moons, Sabbaths) represents the full rhythm of Israel\'s worship year.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>First month, first day: sanctuary purification</strong>: <em>Barishon be\'echad lachodesh tiqach par ben-baqar tamim vechateta et-hamiqdash</em> (\'in the first month, on the first day of the month, you shall take a bull without blemish and purify the sanctuary\'). The yearly calendar of purification begins here: the New Year purification of the sanctuary on 1 Nisan (the spring New Year). This is analogous to but not identical with the Day of Atonement purification of Lev 16 (10 Tishri). Ezekiel\'s calendar separates the priestly purity calendar from the Levitical 7th-month calendar, using a first-month purification for the temple building.</p>',
    "19": '<p><strong>Blood on the doorposts and altar</strong>: The priest takes some of the blood of the purification offering and applies it to the doorposts of the temple, the four corners of the ledge of the altar, and the doorposts of the inner court gate. The blood-smearing ritual echoes the Passover blood on doorposts (Exod 12:7, 22-23) and the altar-consecration blood of Exod 29:12 and Lev 8:15. In both cases, blood marks a threshold as YHWH\'s territory — the purification blood restores the sacred markers of ownership and consecration that may have become "dulled" through the previous year\'s ritual use.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>The seventh day of the first month</strong>: The same purification is performed on the 7th day of the first month, for anyone who sinned inadvertently or through ignorance (<em>bishgagah umin-peti</em>). The inadvertent-sin category (<em>shegagah</em>) from Num 15:22-29 requires atonement for both individual and communal unintentional violations. The repetition of the sanctuary purification on the 7th day creates a week-long purification period that cleanses both the structure (1st day) and the accumulated inadvertent offenses of the community (7th day). The sanctuary is being reset to a pure starting state for the year.</p>',
    "21": '<p><strong>Passover: 14th of the first month</strong>: <em>Barishon bearba\'ah asar yom lachodesh yihyeh lakhem hapesach chag shiv\'at yamim matzot ye\'achel</em> (\'in the first month, on the fourteenth day, you shall have the Passover, a feast of seven days, unleavened bread shall be eaten\'). Passover remains the foundational commemorative feast — the exodus from Egypt. The seven days of unleavened bread correspond to Exod 12:14-20; Lev 23:6-8; Num 28:17-25. The Passover occupies the same calendar position as in the Pentateuch but here is described as a gift of the nasi to the congregation — it is incorporated into the prince\'s liturgical responsibility (v.17).</p>',
    "22": '<p><strong>Passover sin offering: bull for the prince</strong>: On the Passover day, the nasi shall provide a bull as a sin offering for himself and all the people of the land (<em>vela\'am ha\'aretz par chatat</em>). The nasi\'s sin offering is the first sacrifice of the Passover — acknowledging that even the prince stands before YHWH in need of atonement. This leveling function of the sacrifice system is consistent throughout the Torah\'s sacrificial code: the anointed priest (Lev 4:3), the ruler (Lev 4:22), and the common person (Lev 4:27) all bring sin offerings, with the higher role bringing the more costly animal.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>The seven-day Passover burnt offering</strong>: Seven bulls and seven rams daily for seven days (<em>shiv\'at yamim ya\'aseh olah lADONAI shiv\'at parim veshiv\'at eilim temimim liom</em>). This seven-fold offering structure mirrors the Num 28:19 Passover offering schedule. The sin offering is one male goat daily. The seven-day intensity of burnt offerings during Passover reflects the magnitude of the exodus-event being commemorated: the nation\'s founding liberation from Egypt. The sevenfold repetition (7 bulls + 7 rams × 7 days) creates an arithmetic expression of completeness-within-completeness.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>Grain and oil offerings accompanying the Passover</strong>: An ephah of grain offering per bull and ram, and a hin of oil per ephah. The accompaniment of grain and oil with burnt offerings follows the standard formula of Num 15:1-12 where each animal offering is attended by specific grain and liquid measure proportions. The <em>hin</em> of oil per ephah of grain is a generous measure — approximately 1:1 by volume — ensuring substantial quantities of oil are consecrated in the grain offerings. These proportions ground the temple economy in the agricultural reality of grain and olive cultivation in the land.</p>',
    "25": '<p><strong>Feast of Tabernacles: 7th month, 15th day</strong>: <em>Bashvi\'i bachamisha asar yom lachodesh bachag ya\'aseh ka\'elleh shiv\'at yamim</em> (\'in the seventh month, on the fifteenth day of the month, at the feast, shall he do like these things for seven days\'). Sukkot (Tabernacles/Booths) receives the same seven-day burnt offering and sin offering schedule as Passover — a symmetry that brackets the agricultural year: Passover (1 Nisan, spring barley/grain beginning) and Tabernacles (15 Tishri, fall harvest completion). The two feasts frame the agricultural year with its bookend sacrifices, sanctifying the entire agricultural cycle within the covenant calendar.</p>'
},
"46": {
    "1": '<p><strong>The inner east gate on Sabbath and New Moon</strong>: <em>Sha\'ar hechatzer hapniymit hapaneh qadim yihyeh sagur sheshet yemey hama\'aseh</em> (\'the gate of the inner court facing east shall be shut the six working days\'). The same east gate that was discussed in ch44 in relation to the prince\'s access is here given its regular weekly schedule. On Sabbaths and New Moons it is opened (<em>uveyom haShabbat yipatach uveyom hachodesh yipatach</em>) — the elevated sacred days receive elevated architectural access. The gate\'s weekly opening cycle creates a physical expression of the sacred calendar: the gate itself marks time by opening and closing with the rhythm of holy days.</p>',
    "2": '<p><strong>The prince\'s Sabbath and New Moon ritual</strong>: <em>Uvah hanasi derek ulam shaar mihutz</em> (\'the prince shall enter by way of the porch of the gate from outside\'): the nasi enters through the east inner gate porch, stands by the gate doorpost, watches the priests offer his burnt offering and peace offering, and then prostrates himself (<em>vehishtachavah al-miftan hasha\'ar veyatza</em>). The specific exit route — the way he came — is specified. This ritual entry and exit pattern is significant: the nasi participates in the Sabbath worship through observation and prostration at the threshold, the maximum access permitted him short of entering the inner court.</p>',
    "3": '<p><strong>The congregation worships at the outer gate</strong>: The people of the land (<em>am ha\'aretz</em>) prostrate themselves at the entrance to this gate before YHWH on Sabbaths and new moons. The layered worship positions are architecturally enacted: the priests are inside offering at the altar, the prince is at the inner gate porch, the congregation is at the outer gate entrance — each group is as close to YHWH as their status permits. This is a spatial liturgy: the worshipping community is arranged in concentric rings of proximity that express the holiness gradient in real time.</p>',
    "4": '<p><strong>Sabbath burnt offering: six lambs and a ram</strong>: <em>Veha\'olah asher-yaqriv hanasi lADONAI beyom haShabbat shishah kevasim temimim ve\'ayil tamim</em>. The Sabbath offering of six lambs and one ram from the nasi differs from the Num 28:9-10 prescription (two lambs for the Sabbath). The heightened offering in Ezekiel reflects either a more elaborate future liturgy or the increased responsibility of the nasi as the sanctuary\'s fiscal patron. The Sabbath is the temporal center of the weekly cycle just as the inner sanctuary is the spatial center of the temple complex — appropriate that the prince\'s highest weekly sacrifice occurs on the Sabbath.</p>',
    "5": '<p><strong>Grain offering proportions</strong>: An ephah per ram and whatever he can afford (<em>matnat yado</em>) per lamb, and a hin of oil per ephah. The flexible provision for the lamb grain offering (<em>matnat yado</em> = \'the gift of his hand\' = as much as he can give) introduces a pastoral accommodation: the lamb offering\'s grain accompaniment scales with capacity. This is not a reduction of the standard but a recognition that multiplied lamb offerings might require flexible grain quantities. The ram\'s grain offering remains fixed at one ephah — only the more numerous lamb portion is made flexible.</p>',
    "6": '<p><strong>New Moon offering: a bull, six lambs, and a ram</strong>: The New Moon (<em>rosh chodesh</em>) offering adds a bull to the Sabbath formula, making the New Moon the higher of the two regular cycles. This matches the Num 28:11-15 principle that the New Moon offering exceeds the Sabbath offering in number. The bull represents a step up from the Sabbath lamb-and-ram combination, reflecting the New Moon\'s status as a monthly community feast (1 Sam 20:5, 18; Amos 8:5; Isa 1:13-14). The monthly rhythm of the new moon created a punctuation mark in the calendar requiring a more generous public offering.</p>',
    "7": '<p><strong>New Moon grain offerings</strong>: An ephah for the bull, an ephah for the ram, whatever he can afford for the lambs, and a hin of oil per ephah. The grain proportions replicate the Passover grain formula (45:24) — an ephah per major animal (bull/ram) and flexible for lambs. The consistent use of the hin of oil per ephah creates a standard oil-to-grain ratio across all the major offering occasions. This standardization prevents arbitrary escalation or reduction of the offering components — the prince cannot substitute different ratios even if he provides more expensive base animals.</p>',
    "8": '<p><strong>The prince\'s entry and exit pattern</strong>: <em>Uvevo\'o hanasi derek ulam hasha\'ar yavo uvederekh yetze</em> (\'when the prince enters, he shall enter by the way of the gate porch, and by the same way he shall go out\'). The reciprocal entry-exit pattern for ordinary days. The gate-protocol has a theological logic: entering and exiting by the same route prevents the prince from "cutting through" the sacred space — each traversal is intentional and controlled. The prince\'s movements through the sanctuary are liturgical acts, not casual transits.</p>',
    "9": '<p><strong>The congregation\'s entrance and exit pattern</strong>: <em>Uvevo bam ha\'aretz lifney YHWH bamoadim haba derech sha\'ar tzafon lehishtachavot yetze derech sha\'ar negev</em> (\'when the people of the land come before YHWH at the appointed feasts, whoever enters by the north gate to worship shall go out by the south gate\'). The congregation uses a different traffic flow: north-in, south-out (or vice versa). This prevents crowding and creates an orderly flow. The requirement that no one returns by the same entrance gate applies to the entire congregation: the one-way flow ensures that the sacred space is traversed in a directed manner — the congregation moves through the sacred zone rather than oscillating in it.</p>',
    "10": '<p><strong>The prince moves with the people</strong>: <em>Vehanasi betocham bevo\'am yavo uvetseatam yetze\'u</em> (\'and the prince among them — when they enter he shall enter, and when they go out he shall go out\'). The nasi does not have a private worship schedule separate from the congregation: he enters and exits with the people, sharing their liturgical movement. This is the democratic constraint on the nasi\'s elevated liturgical status: he has special gate access and special offering responsibilities, but he moves with his people rather than independently of them. The prince\'s solidarity with the congregation is architecturally enforced.</p>',
    "11": '<p><strong>Feast and festival grain offerings</strong>: At feasts and appointed times, the grain offering shall be an ephah per bull and per ram, and whatever he can afford per lamb, and a hin of oil per ephah. This verse establishes the consistency of the offering formula across all the major occasions: Passover (45:24), New Moon (46:7), Feast of Tabernacles (45:25), and now general feasts — all use the same ephah-per-large-animal and hin-per-ephah formula. The consistency is the point: the sacred calendar operates with uniform mathematical proportions, creating predictability and preventing ad-hoc variation.</p>',
    "12": '<p><strong>Freewill offerings: the east gate opened</strong>: <em>Vechi ya\'aseh hanasi nedavah olah o shelamim nedavah lADONAI</em> (\'and when the prince offers a freewill offering (<em>nedavah</em>), whether a burnt offering or a peace offering, as a freewill offering to YHWH\'). The <em>nedavah</em> (freewill/spontaneous offering) from Lev 22:18-25 is here given a special architectural provision: the east inner gate is opened for it, as on Sabbath and New Moon. The spontaneous devotion of the prince triggers the same gate-opening as the fixed calendar — YHWH receives individual devotion with the same welcome as liturgical obligation. The gate is opened and shut after the prince exits, maintaining its normally-closed status.</p>',
    "13": '<p><strong>The daily morning lamb</strong>: <em>Keves ben-shenato tamim ya\'aseh olah layom tamid</em> (\'a yearling lamb without blemish shall be offered as a burnt offering to YHWH daily — the <em>tamid</em>\'). The <em>tamid</em> (continual/regular) offering of one lamb each morning continues from Exod 29:38-42 and Num 28:3-8, which prescribed two lambs daily (morning and evening). Ezekiel\'s restoration version has only the morning lamb with no evening companion — a simplification or possibly a transitional arrangement. The morning lamb anchors every day in sacrificial worship: the first act of each day is a burnt offering to YHWH.</p>',
    "14": '<p><strong>Daily grain and oil for the tamid</strong>: 1/6 of an ephah of grain and 1/3 of a hin of oil to moisten the flour — a perpetual grain offering, always (<em>chok olam tamid</em>). The perpetual nature of the daily offering system is emphasized by the doubled absolute: <em>chok olam</em> (eternal statute) and <em>tamid</em> (continual). The consistency of the offering formula ensures that the daily sacrifice is never a matter of mood or circumstance — it is an institutional obligation as permanent as the covenant itself. The grain and oil proportions for the morning tamid are specified to prevent arbitrary variation.</p>',
    "15": '<p><strong>Daily lamb, grain, and oil — morning by morning</strong>: <em>Ya\'asu et-hakeves veha-minchah veha-shemen baboqer baboqer olat tamid</em> (\'they shall prepare the lamb, the grain offering, and the oil morning by morning as a perpetual burnt offering\'). The threefold <em>baboqer baboqer</em> (morning by morning) echoes the Exodus manna-gathering formula (baboqer baboqer, Exod 16:21) — each new day begins with YHWH\'s provision meeting Israel\'s need and Israel\'s offering meeting YHWH\'s worship. The daily sacrificial rhythm is Israel\'s covenant heartbeat: as long as the <em>tamid</em> burns, the covenant is active.</p>',
    "16": '<p><strong>The prince\'s inheritance law: sons</strong>: <em>Ki yiten hanasi mattanah le\'achad mibanav nachalatov hi livanaiv tihyeh</em> (\'if the prince gives a gift from his inheritance to one of his sons, it shall be his — it belongs to his sons as a hereditary possession\'). The nasi may permanently alienate portions of his land allocation to his sons. This is a hereditary gift within the family — consistent with the normal inheritance laws. The permanent transfer to sons is the only form of permanent alienation permitted; all other transfers are temporary (reverts at jubilee). The son-permanent/servant-temporary distinction maintains the tribal integrity of land distribution across generations.</p>',
    "17": '<p><strong>Gifts to servants revert at the Jubilee</strong>: <em>Ve\'im yiten mattanah me\'nachalato le\'achad me\'avadav</em> (\'but if he gives a gift from his inheritance to one of his servants\'): the servant\'s gift is temporary, reverting in the year of Jubilee. <em>Halibanaiv tihyeh nachalatam hi</em> (\'for it is their inheritance — it belongs to his sons\'). The Jubilee principle from Lev 25:8-17 governs the prince\'s gift-giving: he cannot permanently impoverish the tribal allotments by giving them to non-tribal members. The annual accumulation that led to the economic disparities condemned in Isa 5:8 (\'woe to those who join house to house\') is structurally prevented by the Jubilee reversion.</p>',
    "18": '<p><strong>The prince shall not take the people\'s inheritance</strong>: <em>Velo yiqach hanasi menahalt ha\'am lehodiham me\'achutzatam</em> (\'the prince shall not take any part of the inheritance of the people, pushing them out of their property\'). This verse explicitly prohibits the Naboth\'s Vineyard scenario (1 Kgs 21) — royal land acquisition by coercion. The nasi may only give from his own allotted territory, not from the people\'s tribal holdings. <em>Lemen lo yafutzu ammi ish me\'achutzato</em> (\'so that my people shall not be scattered each from his property\'): the connection between land tenure and communal stability is explicit — dispossession leads to dispersal, which is the covenant-curse of exile. The restoration order structurally prevents the conditions that led to the pre-exilic social catastrophe.</p>',
    "19": '<p>Ezekiel is led by the gate entrance to the holy chambers of the priests (<em>lishkot haqodesh asher lak-kohanim</em>) facing north. In the westernmost part, there is a place at the two ends. The priestly cooking areas are at the extreme west end of the two side chambers — physically separated from the sacrificial preparation areas to prevent inadvertent transfer of holiness from guilt/sin offerings to other foods. The spatial organization of cooking zones reflects the theological organization of holiness categories: certain offering types are too charged to be handled in proximity to general food preparation.</p>',
    "20": '<p><strong>Where priests cook the guilt and sin offerings</strong>: <em>Zeh hamaqom asher yevashelu sham hakohanim et-he\'asham ve\'et-hachatat</em> (\'this is the place where the priests shall boil the guilt offering and the sin offering\'). The inner cooking courts are the only places where the <em>asham</em> (guilt offering) and <em>chatat</em> (sin offering) may be cooked — both are holy-of-holies offerings (Lev 6:25-29; 7:6-7) that cannot be brought into the outer court lest they consecrate the people there. The principle: <em>lebilti hotzia el-hechatzer hachutzah liqaddesh et-ha\'am</em> (\'so as not to bring them out to the outer court and consecrate the people\'). Holy-of-holies holiness is contagious — it would "charge" anyone who touches the place where these offerings were cooked.</p>',
    "21": '<p>The outer court has four corner courts, each 40 by 30 cubits, and they are of equal size — the four corners of the outer court. The symmetric placement of the four cooking courts at the corners creates a perfectly balanced outer court layout. This architectural symmetry is itself a theological statement: the provision for ordinary people\'s cooking of their peace offerings (as opposed to the inner holy-of-holies offerings) is given equal weight at all four compass points. No direction of the outer court is prioritized over another for ordinary communal meal-preparation.</p>',
    "22": '<p>The four corner courts are enclosed courts, 40 by 30 each. A row of masonry (<em>tira\'ot</em>) is built around the inner edge of each. These small enclosed spaces function as roofed or semi-roofed kitchens — the architectural detail of the surrounding masonry suggests permanent cooking facilities rather than temporary arrangements. The excavation of Iron Age installations at temple sites in the Levant (Tel Arad, Tel Dan) reveals permanent cooking and offering-preparation infrastructure as a standard feature of Israelite cultic sites, confirming the practical necessity of what Ezekiel describes.</p>',
    "23": '<p><strong>The hearths under the surrounding ledge</strong>: <em>Umesharetin tachat hamisgeret saviv saviv</em> (\'and places for boiling beneath the rows around\'). The cooking hearths are built beneath a surrounding ledge — presumably a protective overhang that keeps weather out while allowing smoke to escape. The technical detail of permanent fixed hearths reflects the practical reality that large-scale sacrificial preparation requires substantial, permanent cooking infrastructure. The daily <em>tamid</em> sacrifice plus festival offerings plus peace offerings from thousands of worshippers creates an enormous food-preparation demand that the temple\'s outer court must accommodate.</p>',
    "24": '<p><strong>The cooking courts for the people\'s offerings</strong>: <em>Va\'yomer elay elleh beit hamevashellim asher yevashelu sham mesharetey habayit et-zevach ha\'am</em> (\'and he said to me: these are the boiling houses where the temple ministers shall boil the sacrifice of the people\'). The final verse of ch46 closes the architectural tour with a practical detail: the outer court cooking areas serve the people\'s peace offerings, which are eaten by the worshipper and their family (Lev 7:11-17). The restoration temple provides not just a place for priests to offer and YHWH to dwell, but a full communal meal infrastructure — the sacred feast that bonds Israel to YHWH and to each other is physically built into the temple\'s ground plan.</p>'
}
}

